name: Fine Arts University
section2/finger1: Never saw it happen. But it seems it would be evident when voters physically signed the poll book. However, this particular judge stated that other requirements such as separately counting the two polling stations' voted ballots was not necessary, because electronic scanning of national ID cards was being used in a test situation.
section2/organization: EU, Ministry of Youth, and AP News also filmed closing of this station (which was combined with station 10 at the first day's opening of the polls, apparently on the presiding judge's initiative.)
section3/prevented1: Judge and military personnel would not let us see placement of wax on door where ballots and election supplies were being stored at closing (in a separate campus building in a closet under the entry stairway followed by two locked doors, one internal and one external). We were told to step outside the first door , which put us in a vestibule/foyer. I learned from the rep from the electronics company that the judge began opening the polling place (out of site from observers) at least a full hour ahead of 9am.
section3/obsprevented1: AP was similarly prevented from seeing the wax placed on door where ballots were stored overnight.
section3/other: This polling place was in a stadium-type tiered lecture hall with continuous desktop and benches. All voting took place on the ground floor, and poll workers sat in the first row, while the judge, his female assistant and the tech rep sat on the dais at a table with the judge in the middle. Ballots were centrally issued by the judge after the electronic scanning of national ID cards and passports in a "new technology trial" using the scanners.

name: Fine Arts University
section2/finger1: See answer to this question for station 9.
section2/organization: See answer to this question for station 9, (which station was combined with station 10 so that there was only one ballot box).
section3/prevented1: See answer to this question for station 9
section3/obsprevented1: See answer to this question for station 9.
section3/other: Number of voters in combined polling stations exceeded 3600--too large in number of voters. Judge seemed to believe that the new technology testing allowed him to make his own rules; e.g. combine both ballot boxes into one for two polling stations or fail to affix HEC stamp go backs of ballots. While he was able to quickly give us an exact count of how many had voted: 714 in station 9 and 756 in station 10 as of 8:25 pm, (putting voter turnout before closing of polls on first day at 41%) he had no authority to combine stations for voting and counting purposes. When asked why he didn't use a stamp the ballots, he stated he did not need one, that he could do this because if was the same jurisdiction and that the machine made it unnecessary. The layout of the polling center was so poor that it appeared when a crowd of people walked in at once, that a nun was permitted to obtain her ballot from the judge, who simply asked if she had signed in, without actually signing in. This also appeared to be the case with a woman voter who was carrying a baby. Finally, I asked the judge to see where the number on the closing seal for the single ballot box for two precincts matched the number he had recorded the previous evening. It was recorded on a folded piece of white paper with other writing on it and not on an official reporting form. The judge made his comments that "no other country in the world" has judges running their elections, stating that the people if Egypt trusted their judges.

name: Fine Arts University
section2/organization: EU, Ministry of youth (domestic observer group).
section3/prevented1: Judge argued with us about whether we could witness his closing activities of the polling place. He confirmed he was filling out closing paperwork for stations 7 and 8 and basically told us to leave. We returned to stations 9 and 10 to watch closing there in a separate room of the polling center/building.
section3/obsprevented1: Not certain. They were covering both polling places like we were.
section3/other: Voter counts (turnout) accuracy was aided by the same Morpho/Safran technology as in stations 9 and 10; thus, we were informed with ease that 722 voted in station 7 and 650 in station 8, as of 8:45. Morpho stores voter data both in the cloud and the machine. Morpho equipment for stations 9 and 10 was not locked in the box with ballot supplies. Rather, it was placed back in its equipment case and stored alongside the locked ballot and voting supplies plastic bins in the closet under the stairway in the separate locked building. Since we were unable to view the closing of stations 7 and 8 along with 9 and 10, we can only assume that this was the case also for the Morpho equipment and the ballots and voting supplies for stations 7 and 8. As for polling place layout, workflow and  layout were good with voter flow being from electronic scanning of ID at door, movement of voter to a table to sign in and show ID and get a paper ballot. Voter was allowed to keep own ID. I spoke with the judge the second day about the ability to combine voting districts for the purposes of counting ballots. He said counting should occur according to stations so that ballots could be reconciled according to votes (and presumably according to voted, spoiled and invited ballots.

Because this is a wafadeen (ex pat) station there is no way to tell how many foreigners may show up and therefore if they have enough ballots. Looks promising, as the judges plan to open a 3rd wafadeen box today on top of the 2nd they added yesterday, which was why the judge was signing not stamping the ballots. They don't have two additional stamps for the two new boxes.

They only half secured the ballot box for wafadeen 1 box around 9:26am. They need another plastic lock.
